The paper deals with fundamental graph problems in the Massive Parallel Computation (MPC) framework, which is related to distributed computing and parallel algorithms. Therefore, cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) is the most likely sub-category. The paper specifically focuses on the Maximal Independent Set (MIS) problem, which is a classic problem in graph theory, and proposes a new technique to solve it efficiently on trees with substantially sublinear or subpolynomial memory per machine. This suggests that the paper could also be classified under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The paper also mentions the LOCAL and PRAM models, which are related to computational complexity and parallel computing, respectively, indicating that it could be classified under cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
